Legalization of Cannabis and Its Healthcare and Workplace Consequences

1 Data Description

To explore the impact of legalization of recreational use of cannabis on healthcare and workplace related outcomes, we utilize the IBM Marketscan data base, which contains information on patient-level healthcare claims of employees, retirees, and their dependents insured by employers across different health plans in the United States. The panel data contains state-month observations of U.S. states from 10/2025 to 12/2022.

  • We remove all the observations prior to October 2015.
  • We also remove treated states that do not have at least \(X = 1\) full year of data before or after legalization.

3 Empirical Analyses

To quantify the effect of cannabis legalization, we use the following staggered difference-in-differences (DiD) specification.

\[Y_{it} = \beta Post_{it} + \alpha X_{it} + \delta_i + \eta_t + \epsilon_{it},\] where \(Y_{it}\) is the outcome of interest in state \(i\) and year \(t\); \(Post_{it}\) is a binary indicator for the enactment of legalization laws, which equals 1 for all the years following the enactment in treatment states, and 0 otherwise; \(\delta_i\) is a set of state fixed effects that account for the time-invariant state characteristics; \(\eta_t\) is a set of month fixed effects that account for the national trends that might have impacted the outcome; \(X_{it}\) is a set of time-varying control variables.

An important assumption underlying the DiD specification is that the differences between the outcome in states that legalized the recreational use of cannabis (versus those states that did not legalize) is not due to the pre-existing trends before the legalization, which is know as the parallel trends assumption. To validate this assumption, we estimate the following event-study model (a.k.a. event time analysis) to examine the dynamics in the impact of legalization on the outcome of interest in the treatment states.

\[Y_{it} = \sum_{\tau} \beta_{\tau} time_{i\tau} + \alpha X_{it} + \delta_i + \eta_t + \epsilon_{it},\] where \(time_{i\tau}\) is a set of dummies for the number of months relative to the legalization, and \(\beta_{\tau}\) represents the difference between treatment and control states in period \(\tau\).

The following tables and figures present the results for different outcome variables. In each table, we estimate the models using OLS method with (columns 3-4) and without (columns 1-2) log transformation of the outcome. Moreover, in columns 1 and 3, we do not include time-varying controls. In all models, the robust standard errors are clustered at the state level.

For each outcome, we present the results of our DiD analysis under two scenarios: no lead (baseline) and 6-month lead (where an outcome of interest is measured 6 months from the time of intervention). This is to account for the fact that there might be a delay between legalization and its impact on the outcome variables.
